h3. After creating and embedding an external calendar, I am presented with an intrusively bright orange dialog box in the most prominent spot of all spots that states: 
{quote}
'This calendar is read-only. To work with calendars, please renew your Team Calendars subscription.' 
{quote}

h3. Provide customers with a simple calendar solution directly in Confluence. 

h3. As a suggested workaround, consider implementing an added feature that would allow Admins the ability to dismiss the license message and continue using the calendar as read-only

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-49144].
  {panel}

Linking pages to calendar events is nice. But a deeper integration (like with jira) would be really useful for us.

We would love to have a macro (?) to embed on pages (and page templates!), which automatically creates calendar events and synchronizes them. Of course the macro would have to ask for dates and event type.

Now, the events and pages get out of sync very easy. And there is a high potential, that no events are created at all (because we create the page with a template). And a calender, which you can't rely on, is kinda _dangerous_.

